And the value returned for the `url` will no longer be the location where the file is hosted. Instead it will be a URL that includes `/download/` in the path, similar to below:\n\n```\n[{\n  \"id\": \"5ef22a288dcee602857a9990\",\n  \"url\": \"https://api.trello.com/1/cards/5edfa37673e537161016361c/attachments/5ef22a288dcee602857a9990/download/Screen_Shot_2020-06-23_at_11.13.18_AM.png?signature=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJuYmYiOjE1OTM0NTcyMDAsImV4cCI6MTU5MzQ2MjYwMCwicmVzIjoiNWVkZmEzNzY3M2U1MzcxNjEwMTYzNjFjOjVlZjIyYTI4OGRjZWU2MDI4NTdhOTk5MCIsImlhdCI6MTU5MzQ1OTkwNSwiYXVkIjoiVHJlbGxvIiwiaXNzIjoiVHJlbGxvIn0.8YcOCOFZ4rURYWoiYYEhAEeyQJyMcnSBRo83UviTA_k\"\n}]\n```\n\nThe `/download/` URL format is the following:\n\n> https://api.trello.com/1/cards/{idCard}/attachments/{idAttachment}/download/{attachmentFileName}\n\nThe `url` value returned from the API includes a `signature` parameter which is valid for 1 hour with the `/download/` URL. If you were to make a GET request to the URL without the signature (or after it has expired) you would receive a 401.\n\nMoving forward, there are two options for accessing the file for extended amounts of time.\n\nIf you are using the files directly in your application as a single user, you can add in an API key and token to the request to the `/download/` URL.\n\nMaking a GET request with the key and token will return a 302 that redirects to the URL of the hosted file. You will always be 302'ed so long as the tokened user has access to the attachment. The route you are redirected to is only valid for 1 hour.\n\n**If your application exposes the URL to users other than the one who has granted your application access, you should not use this method.**\n\n---\n\nIf your application needs to give broader access to the file (like showing the file to multiple users), you do not want to leak the key and token, and so you should use the following method of making a preflight HEAD request.\n\nMaking a HEAD request to the `/download/` URL with a valid key and token results in a 302 HTTP response with a `Location:` header that is the URL of the file.\n\nFor instance, here is the HEAD request:\n\n```\ncurl --head https://api.trello.com/1/cards/{idCard}/attachments/{idAttachment}/download/Screen_Shot_2020-06-23_at_11.13.18_AM.png\\?signature\\={signatureFromAbove}\\&token={token}\\&key={key}\n```\n\nAnd our response with the `Location:` header:\n\n```\nHTTP/1.1 302 Found\n[...]\nLocation: https://trello-attachments.s3.amazonaws.com/5edfa37573e53716101635c9/5edfa37673e537161016361c/1fe80390ba5fe13ef04f612c51647f7c/Screen_Shot_2020-06-23_at_11.13.18_AM.png\n[...]\n```\n\nThe URL in the `Location` header is accessible for 1 hour. Your application can safely share that URL for the duration of its validity.\n\n## Opt In To Try New Routes\n\nYou can currently construct the `/download/` routes and pass in authorization. If you pass none of these, the popups will continue to work as they currently do - closing the current view on the stack (the equivalent of calling `t.back()`.\n\nIf you are using a confirm or datetime popup and passing in a callback via `onConfirm`, `callback`, or `onCancel`, you should update the callbacks to explicitly call `t.closePopup()` or `t.back()` or other UI functions as appropriate.\n\nFor instance,\n\n```\nt.popup({\n  type: 'confirm',\n  title: 'Are you sure?',\n  message: 'You are about to do a thing. Can you confirm you want to?',\n  confirmText: 'Confirm',\n  onConfirm: function(t, opts) {\n    // user confirmed the prompt, do whatever you need to do\n    // ...\n    t.closePopup(); // or t.back()\n  },\n  onCancel: function(t, opts)  {\n    // user denied the prompt\n    // ...\n    t.closePopup(); // or t.back()\n  },\n})\n```","descData":null,"due":null,"dueReminder":null,"email":null,"idBoard":"5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef961414","idChecklists":[],"idList":"5e4d4c1cde411f1477332397","idMembers":[],"idMembersVoted":[],"idShort":75,"idAttachmentCover":null,"labels":[{"id":"5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef961437","idBoard":"5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef961414","name":"Update","color":"yellow","uses":40},{"id":"5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef96143a","idBoard":"5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef961414","name":"Power-Ups","color":"purple","uses":55},{"id":"5cffdc0940ce807930ce0fb8","idBoard":"5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef961414","name":"Breaking Change","color":"red","uses":17}],"idLabels":["5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef961437","5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef96143a","5cffdc0940ce807930ce0fb8"],"manualCoverAttachment":false,"name":"Confirm and Datetime Pop-up Changes","pos":49152,"shortLink":"MPtzrlhv","shortUrl":"https://trello.com/c/MPtzrlhv","start":null,"subscribed":null,"url":"https://trello.com/c/MPtzrlhv/75-confirm-and-datetime-pop-up-changes","cover":{"idAttachment":null,"color":null,"idUploadedBackground":null,"size":"normal","brightness":"light","idPlugin":null},"isTemplate":false,"cardRole":null},{"id":"5e0fa6fd242d9630f80e550f","badges":{"attachmentsByType":{"trello":{"board":0,"card":0}},"location":false,"votes":0,"viewingMemberVoted":false,"subscribed":false,"fogbugz":"","checkItems":0,"checkItemsChecked":0,"comments":0,"attachments":0,"description":true,"due":null,"dueComplete":false,"checkItemsEarliestDue":null,"start":null},"checkItemStates":[],"closed":false,"dueComplete":false,"dateLastActivity":"2020-01-03T21:25:50.787Z","desc":"We're removing support for `POST`s and `DELETE`s to `/1/members/idBoardsPinned`.\n\nPreviously, these were used to pin and unpin boards. Signing a URL for an iframe is what allows you to use the client library on the newly opened iframe via the `t.` methods.\n\nWhat we mean by \"signing the url\" is adding context specific to your Power-Up to the url, so that when the secondary iframe is opened, it has the context it needs in order to communicate with Trello. are introducing the ability for developers to specify the allowed origin URLs that their API key can be used with to increase security and trust in the REST API authentication process.\n\nWhen your application is authenticating a user, you may provide a `return_url` that Trello will redirect to after the user gives consent for your application. By default an application key can redirect to any domain, but we strongly recommend that you specify the origins that your application will redirect to when completing authorization.\n\nFor example, if we were GitHub building a GitHub integration for Trello, and we know we will only ever redirect back to `https://github.com` after the user grants access in the auth flow, or perhaps also `http://localhost:3000` for local development, we could add both of those as allowed origins for our application, and no one will be able to use our API key to authenticate users and pass back the token to any other URLs, like `https://bad.example.com`.\n\nYou can view and edit your application's allowed origins at: [https://trello.com/app-key](https://trello.com/app-key). Additionally, you can find more details on the user authorization process here: https://developers.trello.com/page/authorization\n\n*Note:* If your API key has no allowed origins set, then no redirect URL will work. data is handled in a GDPR-compliant fashion, we're adding *Right to Rectification* notifications to the compliance polling response. **This change also requires that public Power-Ups which store personal data for more than 14 days to register an API key.** The API key's secret should be used when polling so that Trello can return member-specific notifications to you.\n\n*tl;dr - Public Power-Ups should not store Trello users' personal data for more than 14 days unless they register an API key and use its secret when polling. New compliance event types will be returned to the `/plugins` compliance polling route.*\n\n### Important Dates\n\n- **API Key Registration Live** - April 22, 2019\n- **RtR Notifications Returned** - May 15, 2019\n\nOn May 15, only public Power-Ups polling the `/plugins` compliance route with the API key's secret will be considered in compliance with Trello's data and privacy practices\n\n### Right To Rectification Notifications\n\nWhat is the right to rectification? Probably easiest to explain by example:\n\n> Let's say your name is Alice Clarkson and you change it to Anne Clarkson. Services, like Trello, that are storing your name should respect this change  and provide a mechanism for this change to be reflected in a reasonable amount of time.\n\nPublic Power-Ups that store personal data beyond a 14 day time window should only store the data for Trello users who have granted access to their accounts via an API token.\n\n**Public Power-Ups will only be considered compliant if they are polling `/1/plugins/{idPlugin}/compliance/memberPrivacy?secret=XYZ` with their API key's secret.**\n\n_Note:_ If you are currently also polling `/1/applications/{key}/compliance/memberPrivacy` this is no longer required, and the route may be deprecated and removed at some point in the future.\n\nCurrently polling the    \"event\": \"tokenExpired\",\n    \"identifier\": \"Matt's App\"\n  }\n]\n```\n\nWhereas, when handling an `accountDeleted` event you should remove any personal data they may have been storing about that member, in response to an `accountUpdated` event you should, within a reasonable time, make sure to update any personal data that you may be storing about that Trello member that has changed. following API updates will go into effect on November 5th. Multi-Board Guests are users who are guests on two or more boards that belong to Business Class team with `products`  `105`, `106`, or `107`. Changes to billing for Business Class teams with Multi-Board Guests will go into effect during the renewal period that follows December 17.\n\n---\n\n**Route:** `PUT /boards/{idBoard}/members/{idMember}`\n\nWhen adding a member to a board if the member is a single board guest and the request is from a non-org-admin, Trello will respond with a 403. To check whether a user is a single board guest or not, you should check for the new `wouldBecomeBillableGuest` param added to the `GET /search/members` as explained below.\n\n*Affected documentation:* [PUT /boards/{idBoard}/members/{idMember}](https://developers.trello.com/v1.0/reference#boardsidlabelnamesmembersidmember)\n\n---\n\n**Route:** `PUT /boards/{idBoard}`\n\nWhen changing whether a board will be part of an organization or not, there is a new parameter `keepBillableGuests` that, when present and has a value of `true`, will leave all users on the board. If the parameter is not included with a value of `true`, members who would become multi-board guests will be removed as a side-effect of the change to the board.\n\nFor instance, when moving a board into a Business Class organization, you'd use the following request:\n\n`PUT /boards/{idBoard}?idOrganization={idOrganization}`\n\nThis request will remove any members from the board that would be charged for as multi-board guests. To keep the new multi-board guests when adding a board to an organization, you should include the `keepBillableGuests` query parameter. For instance:\n\n`PUT /boards/{idBoard}/idOrganization?value={idOrganization}&keepBillableGuests=true`\n\nThe above request would not remove any of the members.\n\nSimilarly, when re-opening a board that belongs to a BC organization, if there are new multi-board guests on the board, they will be removed as a side-effect the following request:\n\n`PUT /boards/{idBoard}?closed=false`\n\nTo keep them on the board, the route accepts the same `keepBillableGuests` parameter:\n\n`PUT /boards/:idBoard/closed?value=false&keepBillableGuests=true`\n\nBoard admins, who are not team admins, can continue to use this route to move and reopen boards. Background\n\nCurrently, it is difficult, or requires awkward workaround to make requests of Trello from your indexConnector iframe, outside the context of a capability.\n\nThis was partially by design, as outside of capabilities which Trello will call when appropriate, your iframe can't know what the current Trello user is up to. And the value returned for the `url` will no longer be the location where the file is hosted. Instead it will be a URL that includes `/download/` in the path, similar to below:\n\n```\n[{\n  \"id\": \"5ef22a288dcee602857a9990\",\n  \"url\": \"https://api.trello.com/1/cards/5edfa37673e537161016361c/attachments/5ef22a288dcee602857a9990/download/Screen_Shot_2020-06-23_at_11.13.18_AM.png?signature=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJuYmYiOjE1OTM0NTcyMDAsImV4cCI6MTU5MzQ2MjYwMCwicmVzIjoiNWVkZmEzNzY3M2U1MzcxNjEwMTYzNjFjOjVlZjIyYTI4OGRjZWU2MDI4NTdhOTk5MCIsImlhdCI6MTU5MzQ1OTkwNSwiYXVkIjoiVHJlbGxvIiwiaXNzIjoiVHJlbGxvIn0.8YcOCOFZ4rURYWoiYYEhAEeyQJyMcnSBRo83UviTA_k\"\n}]\n```\n\nThe `/download/` URL format is the following:\n\n> https://api.trello.com/1/cards/{idCard}/attachments/{idAttachment}/download/{attachmentFileName}\n\nThe `url` value returned from the API includes a `signature` parameter which is valid for 1 hour with the `/download/` URL. If you were to make a GET request to the URL without the signature (or after it has expired) you would receive a 401.\n\nMoving forward, there are two options for accessing the file for extended amounts of time.\n\nIf you are using the files directly in your application as a single user, you can add in an API key and token to the request to the `/download/` URL.\n\nMaking a GET request with the key and token will return a 302 that redirects to the URL of the hosted file. You will always be 302'ed so long as the tokened user has access to the attachment. The route you are redirected to is only valid for 1 hour.\n\n**If your application exposes the URL to users other than the one who has granted your application access, you should not use this method.**\n\n---\n\nIf your application needs to give broader access to the file (like showing the file to multiple users), you do not want to leak the key and token, and so you should use the following method of making a preflight HEAD request.\n\nMaking a HEAD request to the `/download/` URL with a valid key and token results in a 302 HTTP response with a `Location:` header that is the URL of the file.\n\nFor instance, here is the HEAD request:\n\n```\ncurl --head https://api.trello.com/1/cards/{idCard}/attachments/{idAttachment}/download/Screen_Shot_2020-06-23_at_11.13.18_AM.png\\?signature\\={signatureFromAbove}\\&token={token}\\&key={key}\n```\n\nAnd our response with the `Location:` header:\n\n```\nHTTP/1.1 302 Found\n[...]\nLocation: https://trello-attachments.s3.amazonaws.com/5edfa37573e53716101635c9/5edfa37673e537161016361c/1fe80390ba5fe13ef04f612c51647f7c/Screen_Shot_2020-06-23_at_11.13.18_AM.png\n[...]\n```\n\nThe URL in the `Location` header is accessible for 1 hour. Your application can safely share that URL for the duration of its validity.\n\n## Opt In To Try New Routes\n\nYou can currently construct the `/download/` routes and pass in authorization. If you pass none of these, the popups will continue to work as they currently do - closing the current view on the stack (the equivalent of calling `t.back()`.\n\nIf you are using a confirm or datetime popup and passing in a callback via `onConfirm`, `callback`, or `onCancel`, you should update the callbacks to explicitly call `t.closePopup()` or `t.back()` or other UI functions as appropriate.\n\nFor instance,\n\n```\nt.popup({\n  type: 'confirm',\n  title: 'Are you sure?',\n  message: 'You are about to do a thing. Can you confirm you want to?',\n  confirmText: 'Confirm',\n  onConfirm: function(t, opts) {\n    // user confirmed the prompt, do whatever you need to do\n    // ...\n    t.closePopup(); // or t.back()\n  },\n  onCancel: function(t, opts)  {\n    // user denied the prompt\n    // ...\n    t.closePopup(); // or t.back()\n  },\n})\n```","descData":null,"due":null,"dueReminder":null,"email":null,"idBoard":"5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef961414","idChecklists":[],"idList":"5e4d4c1cde411f1477332397","idMembers":[],"idMembersVoted":[],"idShort":75,"idAttachmentCover":null,"labels":[{"id":"5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef961437","idBoard":"5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef961414","name":"Update","color":"yellow","uses":40},{"id":"5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef96143a","idBoard":"5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef961414","name":"Power-Ups","color":"purple","uses":55},{"id":"5cffdc0940ce807930ce0fb8","idBoard":"5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef961414","name":"Breaking Change","color":"red","uses":17}],"idLabels":["5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef961437","5abbe4b7ddc1b351ef96143a","5cffdc0940ce807930ce0fb8"],"manualCoverAttachment":false,"name":"Confirm and Datetime Pop-up Changes","pos":49152,"shortLink":"MPtzrlhv","shortUrl":"https://trello.com/c/MPtzrlhv","start":null,"subscribed":null,"url":"https://trello.com/c/MPtzrlhv/75-confirm-and-datetime-pop-up-changes","cover":{"idAttachment":null,"color":null,"idUploadedBackground":null,"size":"normal","brightness":"light","idPlugin":null},"isTemplate":false,"cardRole":null},{"id":"5e0fa6fd242d9630f80e550f","badges":{"attachmentsByType":{"trello":{"board":0,"card":0}},"location":false,"votes":0,"viewingMemberVoted":false,"subscribed":false,"fogbugz":"","checkItems":0,"checkItemsChecked":0,"comments":0,"attachments":0,"description":true,"due":null,"dueComplete":false,"checkItemsEarliestDue":null,"start":null},"checkItemStates":[],"closed":false,"dueComplete":false,"dateLastActivity":"2020-01-03T21:25:50.787Z","desc":"We're removing support for `POST`s and `DELETE`s to `/1/members/idBoardsPinned`.\n\nPreviously, these were used to pin and unpin boards. Signing a URL for an iframe is what allows you to use the client library on the newly opened iframe via the `t.` methods.\n\nWhat we mean by \"signing the url\" is adding context specific to your Power-Up to the url, so that when the secondary iframe is opened, it has the context it needs in order to communicate with Trello. are introducing the ability for developers to specify the allowed origin URLs that their API key can be used with to increase security and trust in the REST API authentication process.\n\nWhen your application is authenticating a user, you may provide a `return_url` that Trello will redirect to after the user gives consent for your application. By default an application key can redirect to any domain, but we strongly recommend that you specify the origins that your application will redirect to when completing authorization.\n\nFor example, if we were GitHub building a GitHub integration for Trello, and we know we will only ever redirect back to `https://github.com` after the user grants access in the auth flow, or perhaps also `http://localhost:3000` for local development, we could add both of those as allowed origins for our application, and no one will be able to use our API key to authenticate users and pass back the token to any other URLs, like `https://bad.example.com`.\n\nYou can view and edit your application's allowed origins at: [https://trello.com/app-key](https://trello.com/app-key). Additionally, you can find more details on the user authorization process here: https://developers.trello.com/page/authorization\n\n*Note:* If your API key has no allowed origins set, then no redirect URL will work. data is handled in a GDPR-compliant fashion, we're adding *Right to Rectification* notifications to the compliance polling response. **This change also requires that public Power-Ups which store personal data for more than 14 days to register an API key.** The API key's secret should be used when polling so that Trello can return member-specific notifications to you.\n\n*tl;dr - Public Power-Ups should not store Trello users' personal data for more than 14 days unless they register an API key and use its secret when polling. New compliance event types will be returned to the `/plugins` compliance polling route.*\n\n### Important Dates\n\n- **API Key Registration Live** - April 22, 2019\n- **RtR Notifications Returned** - May 15, 2019\n\nOn May 15, only public Power-Ups polling the `/plugins` compliance route with the API key's secret will be considered in compliance with Trello's data and privacy practices\n\n### Right To Rectification Notifications\n\nWhat is the right to rectification? Probably easiest to explain by example:\n\n> Let's say your name is Alice Clarkson and you change it to Anne Clarkson. Services, like Trello, that are storing your name should respect this change  and provide a mechanism for this change to be reflected in a reasonable amount of time.\n\nPublic Power-Ups that store personal data beyond a 14 day time window should only store the data for Trello users who have granted access to their accounts via an API token.\n\n**Public Power-Ups will only be considered compliant if they are polling `/1/plugins/{idPlugin}/compliance/memberPrivacy?secret=XYZ` with their API key's secret.**\n\n_Note:_ If you are currently also polling `/1/applications/{key}/compliance/memberPrivacy` this is no longer required, and the route may be deprecated and removed at some point in the future.\n\nCurrently polling the    \"event\": \"tokenExpired\",\n    \"identifier\": \"Matt's App\"\n  }\n]\n```\n\nWhereas, when handling an `accountDeleted` event you should remove any personal data they may have been storing about that member, in response to an `accountUpdated` event you should, within a reasonable time, make sure to update any personal data that you may be storing about that Trello member that has changed. following API updates will go into effect on November 5th. Multi-Board Guests are users who are guests on two or more boards that belong to Business Class team with `products`  `105`, `106`, or `107`. Changes to billing for Business Class teams with Multi-Board Guests will go into effect during the renewal period that follows December 17.\n\n---\n\n**Route:** `PUT /boards/{idBoard}/members/{idMember}`\n\nWhen adding a member to a board if the member is a single board guest and the request is from a non-org-admin, Trello will respond with a 403. To check whether a user is a single board guest or not, you should check for the new `wouldBecomeBillableGuest` param added to the `GET /search/members` as explained below.\n\n*Affected documentation:* [PUT /boards/{idBoard}/members/{idMember}](https://developers.trello.com/v1.0/reference#boardsidlabelnamesmembersidmember)\n\n---\n\n**Route:** `PUT /boards/{idBoard}`\n\nWhen changing whether a board will be part of an organization or not, there is a new parameter `keepBillableGuests` that, when present and has a value of `true`, will leave all users on the board. If the parameter is not included with a value of `true`, members who would become multi-board guests will be removed as a side-effect of the change to the board.\n\nFor instance, when moving a board into a Business Class organization, you'd use the following request:\n\n`PUT /boards/{idBoard}?idOrganization={idOrganization}`\n\nThis request will remove any members from the board that would be charged for as multi-board guests. To keep the new multi-board guests when adding a board to an organization, you should include the `keepBillableGuests` query parameter. For instance:\n\n`PUT /boards/{idBoard}/idOrganization?value={idOrganization}&keepBillableGuests=true`\n\nThe above request would not remove any of the members.\n\nSimilarly, when re-opening a board that belongs to a BC organization, if there are new multi-board guests on the board, they will be removed as a side-effect the following request:\n\n`PUT /boards/{idBoard}?closed=false`\n\nTo keep them on the board, the route accepts the same `keepBillableGuests` parameter:\n\n`PUT /boards/:idBoard/closed?value=false&keepBillableGuests=true`\n\nBoard admins, who are not team admins, can continue to use this route to move and reopen boards. Background\n\nCurrently, it is difficult, or requires awkward workaround to make requests of Trello from your indexConnector iframe, outside the context of a capability.\n\nThis was partially by design, as outside of capabilities which Trello will call when appropriate, your iframe can't know what the current Trello user is up to.
